<br>
Is either India and/or Pakistan signatories of The Treaty of 1963? <br>
By reading your follow up post it would seem so...<br>
<br>
The copy of the Treaty of 1963 in the first post in this topic states:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Article I</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
1. Each of the Parties to this Treaty undertakes to prohibit, to prevent, and not to carry out any nuclear weapon<br>
test explosion, or any other nuclear explosion, at any place under its<br>
jurisdiction or control:<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
1)India and Pakistan have both test detonated nuclear devices post<br>
treaty... <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> yales wrote:<br>
<br>
India and Pakistan have NEVER violated the LTBT. Not once.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
2)The critical part of the treaty: &quot;not to carry out <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> any</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
nuclear weapon test explosion, or <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> any</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> other nuclear<br>
explosion...&quot;<br>
<br>
It would seem that both India and Pakistan violated the very first<br>
article.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Not a single nuclear treaty has ever been abrogated.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I was hinting at the possibility, not the occurrence. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/15/02 8:49:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ibiblio.org/wm/paint/auth/munch/munch.scream.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear Test Ban Treaty of 1963</span><hr size=1> You missed the relevant clause:<br>
<br>
1. Each of the Parties to this Treaty undertakes to prohibit, to prevent, and not to carry out any nuclear weapon test explosion, or any other nuclear explosion, at any place under its jurisdiction or control: <br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
(a) in the atmosphere; beyond its limits, including outer space; or under water, including territorial waters or high seas; or <br>
===========================================<br>
<br>
The LTBT has zilch to say about underground testing.<br>
ONLY aboveground detonations.<br>
<br>
Nuclear testing proceeded without any hinderence for ~40 years after the LTBT.<br>
<br>
The Soviets didn't end testing until the late '80s and the US in the early '90s.<br>
<br>
The LTBT is an ENVIRONMENTAL treaty, ~not~ really an arms control treaty.<br>
<br>
No one detonates a bomb aboveground. Even the Pakistanis and the Indians adhered to that principle.<br>
<br>
The only detonation one would ever expect above ground is as part of a nuclear holocaust.<br>
<br>
There are no political leaders or major parties anywhere in the world who have ever advocated even the slightest modification of this principle.<br>
<br>
Even Prez G. Bush has strongly endorsed this &quot;sacred&quot; treaty.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
